Both real permittivity and dielectric loss factor increase as GTR content rises. The real permittivity decreases as frequency increases, being this tendency less significant for low GTR concentrations. In the case of HDPE with no GTR, ϵ′ does not depend on the frequency. This drop is due to dielectric dispersion [30,31], but as HDPE is a non-polar material only GTR contributes to such phenomenon. Similar decreases are observed in all the samples studied for the ϵ″ results. In this case, there are contributions of the conductance (
ɛ″'∝σɛ0ω
) and interfacial phenomena at low frequencies. On the other hand, for higher frequencies, it is possible to observe a relaxation in ϵ″ that displays a maximum between 1 × 103 and 1 × 105 Hz. It can be identified with the β relaxation of HDPE, which is related to side-branching in polyethylene.32 As HDPE is not very side-branched, the relaxation is hardly noticed.
